{{Infobox company | name = Smith Brandon International, Inc. | logo = [[File:Smith Brandon International Logo.png|200px|Corporate logo]] | caption = | trading_name = SBI | type = [[Privately held company|Private]] | traded_as = | industry = [[Business intelligence]] | foundation = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]] ({{Start date|1996}}) | founder = {{ubl|[[Harry "Skip" Brandon|Harry B. "Skip" Brandon]]|[[Gene M. Smith]]}} | location_city = [[Washington, D.C.]] | area_served = Worldwide | services = {{ubl|[[Due diligence]]|[[private investigator|Corporate investigations]]}} | homepage = [http://www.smithbrandon.com www.smithbrandon.com] | footnotes = | bodystyle = }}
'''Smith Brandon International, Inc. (SBI)''' is an [[United States|American]] boutique [[Private investigator|corporate investigations]] and [[Risk and strategic consulting|risk consulting]] firm based in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name="FAQ">{{cite web |url= http://www.smithbrandon.com/faq.html |title=Frequently Asked Questions |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |publisher= |work=Smith Brandon International |accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> It was founded in 1996 by [[Gene M. Smith]] and [[Harry "Skip" Brandon]] and today employs a worldwide network of investigators, including former heads of law enforcement agencies, political figures and professionals with legal, financial and intelligence backgrounds.<ref name="Ottawa">{{cite journal |last1=Fields |first1=Julia |date=August 1999 |title=Intelligence firm profits from overseas contacts |journal=Ottawa Business Journal |pages=10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.smithbrandon.com/about-sbi.html |title=About SBI |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |publisher= |work=Smith Brandon International |accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> SBI offers a range of services, including high-level political analysis, global due diligence, risk avoidance, corporate investigations, financial investigations, political risk assessments and business intelligence services.<ref name="FAQ"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Insecurity and fear feed a once secretive industry |last=Larsen|first=Peter Thal|authorlink=Peter Thal Larsen |newspaper=Financial Times |date=April 11, 2002 }}</ref>
SBI does not disclose the names of its clients or the specifics of its projects.<ref name="Ottawa"/><ref name="Ripley">{{cite news |title=Rent-a-Spook |author=Ripley, Amanda |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/15527/rent-a-spook |newspaper=Washington City Paper |date=July 31, 1998 |accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> However, SBI's clients include domestic and foreign [[Fortune 500|Fortune 50]] companies, as well as [[Small and medium enterprises|small- and medium-sized companies]], working internationally in many industries, such as banking, oil, mining and timber.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Dogs of Peace |author=Stein, Jeff |url= http://www.salon.com/1996/11/20/news_586/ |newspaper=Salon |date=November 20, 1996 |accessdate=February 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Risk Analysts Cut a Path for Latin American Investors |author=Whitefield, Mimi |newspaper=The Miami Herald |date=April 20, 1998 }}</ref><ref name="Impact21">{{cite journal |last1=Stein |first1=Jeff |date=March 1997 |title=Risky Business |journal=Impact 21 |pages=22–25 }}</ref> With assistance from its international network of contacts in the intelligence, business and diplomatic communities, SBI has worked across [[North America]], [[Latin America]], the [[Middle East]], [[Asia]], [[Africa]] and [[India]].<ref name="Ripley"/><ref name="Impact21"/><ref>{{cite news |title=The top players in intelligence industry |author=Andrew Edgecliffe-Johnson |newspaper=Financial Times |date=April 10, 2001 }}</ref> Ninety-five percent of their work is outside of the U.S.<ref name="HBR">{{cite journal |last1=Finder |first1=Joseph |year=2007 |title=The CEO's Private Investigation |journal=Harvard Business Review |volume=85 |issue=10 |pages=54 |publisher=Harvard Business Publishing |url= http://hbr.org/2007/10/the-ceos-private-investigation/ar/1 |accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref>
Founders Smith and Brandon have had close ties with U.S. governmental agencies; Smith was an agent for the [[CIA]] and Brandon was deputy assistant director of the National Security and Counter Terrorism programs for the [[FBI]].<ref name="Ripley"/><ref>{{cite interview |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0404/16/lol.06.html |last=Brandon |first=Harry |subjectlink = Harry Brandon |interviewer=Soledad O’Brien |title=Can FBI & CIA Work Together? |work=[[CNN]] |date=August 16, 2004 |accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref> Both have contributed to various industry journals, such as the [[Harvard Business Review]], and have spoken at various conferences and on national radio programs, including [[NPR]]’s [[Talk of the Nation]].<ref name="HBR"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brandon |first1=Harry |last2=Smith |first2=Gene M. |date=March–April 1998 |title=Coping with Disaster: You Need a Plan |journal=MiningVoice |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=23–27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brandon |first1=Harry |last2=Smith |first2=Gene M. |date=March 1999 |title=Expert Advisor: Expect the Unexpected—Terrorism in Today's World |journal=Crime Victims Litigation |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=10–11 |publisher=The National Center of Victims of Crime}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Gene M. |date=November–December 2000 |title=Credit Risk and Risk Avoidance |journal=Business Credit |volume=102 |issue=10 |pages=58–59 }}</ref><ref>{{cite interview |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4803987 |last=Brandon |first=Harry |subjectlink = Harry Brandon |interviewer=Neil Conan |title=Talk of the Nation |work=[[National Public Radio]] |publisher=[[WBUR]] |location =Boston, Massachusetts |date=August 17, 2005 |accessdate=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Gene M. |year=2010 |title=Challenges in International Security: Kidnapping & Crisis Management |journal=Journal of the Washington Institute of China Studies |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=71–76 |publisher=The Washington Institute of China Studies |url= http://www.wics-usa.org/journal/Papers/Spring-2010/2010Spring-06-ChallengesinInternationalSecurity.pdf |accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |url= http://web.bryant.edu/~aibne/program.htm |first1=Gene M. |last1=Smith |first2=Harry |last2=Brandon |date=October 9, 2004 |conference=Academy of International Business – Northeast USA 2004 Annual Conference |location=Smithfield, Rhode Island |accessdate=February 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |url= http://184.168.136.190/ief/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=102&Itemid=620 |first=Harry |last=Brandon |date=May 15, 2012 |conference=India Enterprise Forum |location=Dallas, Texas |accessdate=February 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=FCIB 1st International Credit & Risk Management Conference in the Middle East |author= Stensgaard, Anne-Birte |url=http://www.ameinfo.com/55286.html |work=AMEinfo.com |date=March 7, 2005 |accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref>
